---
import BlogPostLayout from '../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BlogPostLayout
  title="5 Flutter performance mistakes I made so you don't have to"
  description="Jank, memory leaks, unnecessary rebuilds — a tour of the performance issues I've debugged over the years and how to avoid them."
  canonicalUrl="https://waseemarain4u.github.io/my-portfolio/blog-article-performance"
  ogImage="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1461749280684-dccba630e2f6?w=1200&q=80"
  tag="Performance"
  date="Dec 2, 2024"
  readTime="7 min read"
>
  <p>Flutter apps are fast by default — until they aren't. I've debugged enough jank, memory pressure issues, and frame drops across production apps to have strong opinions about where Flutter performance problems actually come from.</p>

  <h2>1. Rebuilding the entire widget tree on state changes</h2>
  <p>This is the most common mistake I see in Flutter codebases. A single ChangeNotifier or BLoC state update triggers a rebuild at the top of the tree, and Flutter re-renders widgets that have nothing to do with the changed data. The fix is straightforward: push state as low as possible, use <code>const</code> constructors everywhere you can, and wrap expensive subtrees in <code>RepaintBoundary</code>.</p>
  <pre>// Don't do this — rebuilds the whole screen
Consumer&lt;AppState&gt;(builder: (ctx, state, _) =&gt; Scaffold(...));

// Do this — rebuilds only the widget that needs the data
Consumer&lt;AppState&gt;(builder: (ctx, state, _) =&gt; Text(state.username));</pre>

  <h2>2. Heavy work on the main isolate</h2>
  <p>JSON parsing, image processing, and database queries run on the main thread by default. On large payloads this causes visible frame drops. Move anything that takes more than a few milliseconds to a separate isolate using <code>compute()</code> or Flutter's Isolate API.</p>

  <h2>3. Not disposing controllers and streams</h2>
  <p>TextEditingControllers, AnimationControllers, StreamSubscriptions — all of these leak memory if you don't dispose them. I've seen apps with gradual memory growth that was entirely caused by controllers created in <code>initState</code> and never cleaned up. Always override <code>dispose()</code>. Always.</p>

  <h2>4. Loading full-resolution images</h2>
  <p>Loading a 4K photo to display in a 50x50 avatar thumbnail is a surprisingly common performance issue. Use <code>cacheWidth</code> and <code>cacheHeight</code> parameters on <code>Image.network</code> to decode images at the size they'll actually be displayed. On image-heavy screens, this alone can cut memory usage significantly.</p>

  <h2>5. Animating with setState</h2>
  <p>Using <code>setState</code> inside an animation callback rebuilds the whole widget on every frame. Use <code>AnimatedBuilder</code> or <code>AnimatedWidget</code> instead — they limit the rebuild to only the animated portion of the tree. On complex screens this is the difference between smooth 60fps and visible jank.</p>
  <p>The Flutter DevTools performance tab is your best friend for diagnosing all of these. Profile in release mode — debug mode is much slower and will give you misleading results.</p>

  <div slot="more-articles">
    <section class="bg-zinc-50 dark:bg-zinc-900/40 py-16">
      <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6">
        <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-2xl text-zinc-900 dark:text-white mb-8">More articles</h2>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
          {[
            { href: 'blog-article', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1607252650355-f7fd0460ccdb?w=700&q=80', alt: 'Clean Architecture', date: 'May 10, 2025', title: 'Why I switched from MVC to Clean Architecture in Flutter' },
            { href: 'blog-article-bloc', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516321318423-f06f85e504b3?w=700&q=80', alt: 'State management', date: 'Feb 18, 2025', title: 'BLoC, Riverpod, or Provider? My honest take after 4 years' },
            { href: 'blog-article-kotlin', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1555099962-4199c345e5dd?w=700&q=80', alt: 'Kotlin', date: 'Apr 3, 2025', title: 'Kotlin vs Java in 2025: when to still choose Java' },
          ].map(p => (
            <article class="group bg-white dark:bg-zinc-900 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-zinc-100 dark:border-zinc-800 hover:border-accent transition-all hover:-translate-y-1">
              <div class="pf w-full h-40"><img src={p.img} alt={p.alt} loading="lazy"></div>
              <div class="p-5">
                <p class="text-xs text-zinc-400 mb-2">{p.date}</p>
                <a href={`${base}${p.href}`}><h3 class="font-display font-bold text-base text-zinc-900 dark:text-white group-hover:text-accent transition-colors">{p.title}</h3></a>
              </div>
            </article>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</BlogPostLayout>
